Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the rigatoni.

Pick the @sage{1} leaves from their stalks (discard the stalks). Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a garlic press).

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the sage leaves in a single layer. Fry until crispy, ~{1-2%mins}.

Transfer to a #plate{} lined with kitchen paper.

When your pan of water is boiling, add the @rigatoni pasta{180%g} and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%mins}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

While the pasta cooks, pop the (now empty) frying pan back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{} if needed.

Once hot, add the onion and @British pork and oregano sausage meat{225%g}. Fry until everything's browned, ~{5-6%mins}.

Use a #spoon{} to break the sausage meat up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The sausage meat is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the garlic to the frying pan and cook for ~{1%min}.

Stir in the @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @baby spinach{100%g} and @water{75%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for amount). Bring to the boil, then turn the heat down and cook until the spinach is wilted and the sauce has slightly thickened, ~{3-4%mins}.

Once thickened, stir through the cooked rigatoni, @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g} and @creme fraiche{75%g} until everything's piping hot.

Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little too thick.

When your pasta is ready, taste and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed, then share between your #bowls{}.

Grind over some extra @ground black pepper{} and crumble the crispy sage over the top to finish.

Enjoy!